  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How did people communicate in the pre-internet era?",
  "response": "Before the internet revolutionized communication, people relied on various traditional methods to exchange information and stay connected. Here are some of the primary means of communication in the pre-internet era:\n\n1. **Letters and Postcards**: People commonly wrote letters to each other, which involved using postal services. This method allowed for detailed and personalized communication, though it could take days or even weeks for messages to be delivered, especially over long distances.\n\n2. **Telegraph**: Introduced in the 19th century, the telegraph allowed messages to be sent long distances quickly using Morse code. It was a significant advancement in reducing the time it took to communicate across distances.\n\n3. **Telephone**: Invented in the late 19th century, telephones provided a more immediate and personal way to communicate as people could talk to each other in real time. This significantly changed personal and business communication.\n\n4. **Radio**: Radio broadcasts began in the early 20th century and became a popular means of disseminating news, entertainment, and information to a wide audience. It was one of the first mass media technologies.\n\n5. **Television**: With its introduction in the mid-20th century, television became a dominant medium for entertainment and information, reaching households with news, educational programs, and various forms of entertainment.\n\n6. **Newspapers and Magazines**: These print media were major sources of news and information. People relied on newspapers and magazines to stay informed about local, national, and international events.\n\n7. **Face-to-Face Meetings**: Personal meetings and gatherings were crucial for communication. People often met in person for business, social, and community discussions.\n\n8. **Word of Mouth**: Information was also passed along informally through conversations within communities, families, and social networks.\n\n9. **Faxes**: In the latter half of the 20th century, fax machines became a way to send copies of documents quickly over telephone lines. This was particularly useful for businesses.\n\nEach of these methods had its limitations and advantages, shaping the way people interacted and exchanged information before the emergence of the internet.",
